      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The Civil Rights Movement was marked by internal conflicts and disagreements, particularly between the leadership of Martin Luther King Jr. and Malcolm X, who had fundamentally different approaches to achieving racial equality. King's emphasis on nonviolent civil disobedience often put him at odds with more militant groups like the Black Panther Party, who advocated for armed self-defense and more radical change. Additionally, the Southern Christian Leadership Conference (SCLC) and the Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee (SNCC) had differing strategies and ideologies, leading to tensions and power struggles within the movement. Despite these conflicts, the movement's shared goal of achieving racial justice ultimately drove its progress.",
